                                <h1 itemprop="headline" class="articleHeadline">Q&amp;A</h1>
                                <h6 class="byline">
                                    <span itemprop="author creator" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <span itemprop="name">By J. D. BIERSDORFER</span>
                                    </span>
                                </h6>
                                <h6 class="dateline">Published: January 17, 2008</h6>
                                <div class="shareTools shareToolsThemeClassic articleShareToolsTop" data-shares="facebook,twitter,google,email,showall|Share,print,singlepage,reprints,ad" data-title="Q&amp;A" data-url="https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C07E2DE103DF934A25752C0A96E9C8B63"
                                    data-description="Staying Private
&lt;p&gt;
  On Facebook
&lt;p&gt;"></div>
                                <meta name="emailThisHash" content="z3xnC0bTwrTXZIKnFPg5og">
                                <div class="articleBody">
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        Staying Private </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        On Facebook </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        Q.How much information from my Facebook profile can random people find out about me with a regular Web search? </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        A. Facebook announced last fall that it was making limited member profiles visible on the Web for people who are not members of the social networking site. While the information revealed about you is limited to your name and profile photo, you can edit
                                        your privacy settings to limit what the general public -- as well as Facebook members -- can see. </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        To adjust your privacy preferences, log into your Facebook account and click the Privacy link in the top right corner of your home page. On the Privacy Overview page, you will find links to the aspects of your Facebook profile that you can control. For
                                        example, click the Search link to limit which Facebook users can find you in a search -- everyone, people in your network or just the users you have tagged as friends. </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        You can also choose on this page whether to let people outside Facebook see your information. Make sure the box for your &apos;&apos;public search listing&apos;&apos; is not checked if you don&apos;t want to be found by search engines. If you want to
                                        be found, you can specify here what people can see or do if they find you, like viewing your photo. </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        Aside from your search privacy settings, the Privacy Overview page has plenty of other options to adjust if you want to limit what people, Facebook applications or even external Web sites can display on your profile page. You can also choose to block
                                        or limit your profile to specific users. </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        Making iTunes </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        Behave on a Mac </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        Q.Every time I put a blank CD into my Mac, iTunes pops up, even if I just want to burn photos to the disc. How can I burn the pictures? </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        A. Mac OS X lets you assign certain system actions when you put a CD or DVD into the disc drive. One of the actions for inserting a blank disc is to have iTunes always open, but you can change this behavior. </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        Open the System Preferences on the Mac by clicking on its icon down in the Dock or by going to the Apple menu in the top left corner of the screen and choosing System Preferences. When the panel opens, click on the icon in the Hardware area, CDs &amp;
                                        DVDs. </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        In the CDs &amp; DVDs preferences, you can opt to have the Mac open a specific program, show the disc on the desktop or even ask you what to do each time you put in a blank CD. If you choose to have the CD open in the Finder, you can then drag the photos
                                        you want to burn onto the desktop CD icon. Once you have your photos copied to the disc, you can burn the CD by clicking the black-and-yellow icon next to it in the Finder window, or by choosing the Burn Disc option
                                        from the File menu. </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        TIP OF THE WEEK If your finger is tired of turning the wheel in the middle of a computer mouse to roll through a page, press down on the scroll-wheel button. Arrows appear and you scroll just by moving the mouse up and down. </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        Click the scroll wheel again to return to normal scrolling. The trick works on many Web browsers and in long documents in some versions of Microsoft Word. Firefox users have another shortcut with the scroll-wheel button: click on a link to open that link
                                        in a new browser tab. J. D. BIERSDORFER </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        Questions about computer-based technology may be sent to QandA @nytimes.com. This weekly column will address questions of general interest, but e-mail and letters cannot be answered individually. </p>
                                </div>
